==English==
===Etymology===
Gr. [[σιγμοειδής]] (sigmoīdēs), from [[σίγμα]] or [[σῖγμα]] (sigma) "sigma" + [[εἶδος]] (īdos) "form, likeness".  Compare with French [[sigmoïde]].

===Pronunciation===
IPA: [[WEAE]] /ˈsɪg.mɔɪd/

===Adjective===
[[Image:S-shape.PNG|right|thumb|Crude rendering of variations on the sigmoid shape]]
'''sigmoid''', alternate '''sigmoidal'''
<!-- some material copied from Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary (1913) -->
# {{geometry}} Curved in two directions, like the letter &ldquo;S&rdquo;, or the Greek &ldquo;ς&rdquo; (sigma).
# {{anatomy}} Relating to the [[sigmoid flexure]].

====Related Terms====

[[Sigmoid flexure]] also [[Sigmoid colon]] (Anatomy) = the last curve of the colon before it terminates in the rectum.

[[Sigmoid valve]]s (Anatomy) = another name for [[Semilunar valve]]s.

[[Sigmoid arteries]] (Anatomy) = [[arteriae sigmoideae]], the arteries in the sigmoid flexure (not S-shaped arteries).

[[Sigmoid fossa]] also [[Sigmoid sinus]] or [[Sigmoid groove]] (Anatomy)

===Noun===
# {{math}} A function having a graph shaped like a sigmoid.  See [[w:Sigmoid|Wikipedia]], [http://mathworld.wolfram.com/SigmoidFunction.html Mathworld].

